rganize against the Pahlavi regime and earn the support of empathetic Americans. Together they rejected the Shah’s authoritarian model of development and called for civil and political rights in Iran, giving unwitting support to the rise of the Islamic Republic of Iran.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aEducational exchangeszIranxHistoryy20th century. 0aEducational exchangeszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aIranian studentszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 4aInternational Studies. 4aMiddle East Studies. 4aU.S. History.  aUS-Iran relations, international education, Cold War diplomacy, soft power, transnational history, political significance of education, Iranian-American alliance.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311066587140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781501709708?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501709708423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501709708/original  a978-3-11-066587-1  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_PPALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles